Article 2

From: strnlght@netcom.com (David Sternlight)
Subject: Re: Over 10,000 Have Signed Petition to Oppose Clipper

In article <2k66nd$341@access1.digex.net>,
Steve Brinich <steve-b@access1.digex.net> wrote:

[The next two lines actually belong to David Sternlight - bjf]

> > 500 to 1. I doubt that very much. Now CPSR is claiming 20,000
> >"signatures" and I give you a guarantee that most are forgeries.
>
> Still willing to put money on it? Name an amount (up to $100), a
>definition of "most" (down to 90%), and a procedure by which your claim
>can be proven and I'll take you up on it.

A small experiment is underway now. It will use decision-theoretic
Bayesian analysis for evaluation of the results, a la Raiffa and 
Schlaifer of the Harvard Business School. So far the results aren't
remotely supportive of the hypothesis that CPSR's 20,000 signatures are 
genuine.

Note to those unfamiliar with this method of analysis: What is being done
is seeking confirmation, examining the confirmations to avoid a repeat of
any bogus signatures, and then asking the question: If there were 20,000
distinct and genuine signatures, what's the probability that we'd get the
results of the confirmation experiment we actually got? If that
probability is very small, it does not support the hypothesis that there 
actually were 20,000 distinct and genuine signatures.

Putting it even more simply, we're conducting an experiment. We then say,
suppose CPSR's results aren't "rigged" by those "voting". What's the
chance we would get the result of the experiment we did? If the chance is

high, that suggests that CPSR's results aren't "rigged" by the
respondents. If the chance is low, that suggests that CPSR's results
were rigged by the respondents, and CPSR should place little confidence
in them.

I won't get into the details of the experiment until the results of it
are in, since to do so might bias the experiment itself. Suffice it to
say that so far the results aren't remotely supportive of the hypothesis
that CPSR received 20,000, or even 10,000 responses from as many
different real U.S. persons, or even persons regardless of nation.

David


